
1. What is Streamlit and why is it popular?

Streamlit is an open-source Python framework that transpiles Python scripts into React-based web applications through a reactive execution model. Its adoption (50K+ GitHub stars, 2026) stems from solving the frontend-backend impedance mismatch for data scientists.

Core Technical Advantages:

text
• Zero frontend stack (HTML/CSS/JS abstraction)
• Script → Dashboard conversion in <100 LOC 
• Native pandas/matplotlib/scikit-learn integration
• Hot-reload development server (500ms TTFB)

Engineering Metrics (vs Flask):

| Metric                  | Streamlit | Flask + React |
| ----------------------- | --------- | ------------- |
| Time-to-first-dashboard | 15 mins   | 2-3 days      |
| LOC for ML demo         | ~50       | ~500          |
| Hot reload latency      | 200ms     | Manual        |



2. How is Streamlit different from normal web development?

Fundamental Paradigm Shift:

Traditional Web Stack:
Frontend (React/Vue) ↔ API (Flask/FastAPI) ↔ ORM/DB
↓ 3 codebases, CORS, state sync, auth layers

Streamlit Single-Threaded Reactive Model:

Python Script (.py) → Streamlit Runtime → React DOM
↕️ Widget interaction triggers full script re-execution

Key Technical Differences:

| Aspect              | Traditional MVC          | Streamlit                         |
| ------------------- | ------------------------ | --------------------------------- |
| State Management    | Redux/Context API        | @st.session_state (auto-persists) |
| Component Lifecycle | useEffect/useState       | Script re-run top-to-bottom       |
| Data Binding        | Manual API calls         | Native pandas → st.dataframe      |
| Routing             | React Router             | st.switch_page() (file-based)     |
| Build Pipeline      | Webpack + Backend deploy | Single streamlit run app.py       |

Performance Tradeoff: O(n) re-execution vs traditional O(1) targeted updates.



